<div id="review_4501815650" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4501815650" />
    <a title="Jalilah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4656570-jalilah"><img alt="Jalilah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577750741p2/4656570.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4501815650?book_show_action=true">Jan 28, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jalilah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jalilah" href="/user/show/4656570-jalilah">Jalilah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781846590108" href="/book/show/155766.For_Bread_Alone">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4656570-jalilah?shelf=middle-east-north-africa">middle-east-north-africa</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4656570-jalilah?shelf=2022-mena-lit-challenge">2022-mena-lit-challenge</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4501815650" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4978731935483312473">This book is a reread for me I first read it in the late 80s. It will always be a 5 star book for me. Regardless of all the violence and brutality, it is a compelling read. It is real. The violence is not exploitive, the sex not meant to be titillating. It is meant to be a protest. <br/>This is because the story mirrors the author&apos;s own life. Like Mohamed in For Bread Alone, Mohamed Choukri was born into extreme poverty. His father was extremely abusive and Mohamed never went to school. As a child he</span>
  <span id="freeText4978731935483312473" style="display:none">This book is a reread for me I first read it in the late 80s. It will always be a 5 star book for me. Regardless of all the violence and brutality, it is a compelling read. It is real. The violence is not exploitive, the sex not meant to be titillating. It is meant to be a protest. <br />This is because the story mirrors the author's own life. Like Mohamed in For Bread Alone, Mohamed Choukri was born into extreme poverty. His father was extremely abusive and Mohamed never went to school. As a child he was already pickpocketing and as a teen taking drugs and alcohol going to sex workers and involved in other petty crimes before going to jail. He did not learn to read until he was 20. It was when he met the American author Paul Bowles who translated this novel into English, that Choukry began writing. He also frequented with other authors who lived in Tanger like Tennessee Williams and Jean Genet. Although these authors might have influenced him to some degree, Choukry has his own unique style which is also very Moroccan. Although his works were initially banned, he is now considered a great literary figure in Morocco. <br />This is a quote by Mohamed Choukry: “I cannot write about the milk of birds, the gentle stranglehold of the angelic beauty, grasps of dew, the cascade of lions, the heavy breast of females. I cannot write with a crystal’s paintbrush. For me, writing is a protest, not a parade.”</span>
  <a data-text-id="4978731935483312473" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


