    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2283759503" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2283759503" />
    <a title="Michael Haase" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/36432305-michael-haase"><img alt="Michael Haase" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1498749694p2/36432305.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2283759503?book_show_action=true">Feb 04, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael Haase" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael Haase" href="/user/show/36432305-michael-haase">Michael Haase</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9782757818824" href="/book/show/387926.Le_pain_nu">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2283759503" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9743314465042161747">This is destitution at its height, although &apos;height&apos; may be the wrong word in this case. In point fact, this book gauges how low a human being can fall in order to survive. This is the kind of novel that raises many questions, some existential, such as, &quot;what reason could there be in living under such dire conditions&quot;, some more mundane, like, &quot;why should I keep reading such a sick and disturbing book?&quot; But read on you do, because the novel&apos;s visceral hideousness conflicts with the naturally ord</span>
  <span id="freeText9743314465042161747" style="display:none">This is destitution at its height, although 'height' may be the wrong word in this case. In point fact, this book gauges how low a human being can fall in order to survive. This is the kind of novel that raises many questions, some existential, such as, "what reason could there be in living under such dire conditions", some more mundane, like, "why should I keep reading such a sick and disturbing book?" But read on you do, because the novel's visceral hideousness conflicts with the naturally ordered and peaceful worldview people generally maintain. The average man doesn't want to acknowledge that his world may well be rife with every imaginable manner of suffering, although he might not see it in front of him. The novel is both intriguing and frightening, and so the mingled senses of curiosity and apprehension drive the reader to continue until the end.<br /><br />Now, Choukri is no poet, in my opinion, but he does society a great contribution buy revealing desperate circumstances, hopefully leading to understanding from the people and well-needed legislative reform from the government. I'd like to say it has, based on the book's international recognition and Choukri's acceptance into the modern-day Moroccan literary curriculum, but that would be conjecture. I've never been to Morocco, so I can't say for certain. <br /><br />While the book is itself deeply fascinating (if not disquieting), I found a likewise fascinating phenomenon as I was reading the translations. I have copies in English (translated by Paul Bowles) and in French (translated by Ben Jelloun), and what I noticed was a vast difference between the two. The English translation appears to have been <i>heavily</i> redacted, although 'redacted' is an insufficient term for it. 'transformed' would more apt. Not only does the English adulterize much of the violence and sex throughout the novel, but it frequently cuts bits and pieces of the text, sometimes entire pages worth of writing. An entire 4-page dialogue about the treatment of women is absent in the English version, as well as songs, descriptions of hard labor, a sex scene between the Choukri's parents with a direct reference to Choukri's own nascent sexuality, and even a part where a friend of Choukri mentions how his uncle murdered himself and his family to avoid shameful poverty. Sentences with sexual overtones are softened, such as the word 'siren' somehow becomes 'wild duck', and the passage, <br /><br /><i>"Je sentais de plus en plus le désir sexuel s'éveille en moi. Il m'habitait avec force at insistance. Mes femelle n'etaient autres que les poules, les chèvres, les chiennes, les genisses..."</i><br /><br />became<br /><br /><i>"Each day the sight of certain living creatures produced great excitement in me: hens, goats, dogs and calves. Many hens died as a result of my experiments."</i> <br /><br />The provocative phrase, <i>"désir sexuel"</i>, was turned into the more innocuous term, <i>"excitement"</i>, and the word <i>"femelles"</i> is absent in English. Then the sentence: <i>"Many hens died as a result of my experiments."</i> is added for comedic relief, taking away the gravity of the passage, which the phrase <i>" Il m'habitait avec force at insistance. "</i> accentuates.<br /><br />I could make a case study on the nature of censorship in different countries using this book as my primary source. I understand the French version is a translation as well, and is likely missing significant elements of the text, but I did a cross check with a friend who knew Arabic and the French version appears more faithful to the text. This could be because it's translator is another Moroccan novelist, rather than an American ex-patriot, but that could also just be beside the point. In all circumstances, if possible, avoid reading the English copy. It's a shameful rejection of the principle of freedom of speech. A book, however profane and disgusting it is, should never be censored like this.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9743314465042161747" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


