  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2844802483" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2844802483" />
    <a title="Basel " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/96942433-basel"><img alt="Basel " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1557195609p2/96942433.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2844802483?book_show_action=true">Jun 04, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Basel " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Basel " href="/user/show/96942433-basel">Basel </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/96942433-basel?shelf=moroccan">moroccan</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2844802483" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15265664014710235033">Some works of literature transport you elsewhere. Some make you happy. Some make you sad. Some make you smile. Some make you frown. Some shake you to the core. The Naked Bread (Known in English under the title “For Bread Alone” and “Le Pain Nu” in French) is an autobiographical novel by the Moroccan author Mohamed Choukri. This book just shook me as I read it. Choukri traces the first 20 years of his life living a miserable and brutal life between the countryside of Tangiers and moving around, a</span>
  <span id="freeText15265664014710235033" style="display:none">Some works of literature transport you elsewhere. Some make you happy. Some make you sad. Some make you smile. Some make you frown. Some shake you to the core. The Naked Bread (Known in English under the title “For Bread Alone” and “Le Pain Nu” in French) is an autobiographical novel by the Moroccan author Mohamed Choukri. This book just shook me as I read it. Choukri traces the first 20 years of his life living a miserable and brutal life between the countryside of Tangiers and moving around, always with misery, searching for that piece of bread to fill up his stomach. We learn of his relationships with his family. We learn of his sexual exploits and sexual awakening. We learning of the brutal life of living without a home, and we accompany him throughout his 20 years of being illiterate until he finally decides he will be illiterate no more. He will read and write. <br /><br />Choukri’s autobiography is extremely raw. No wonder it was first censured when it came it out. While reading some very graphic scenes of it, I found myself unconsciously distancing the book from myself, just thinking to myself that I shouldn’t read this. It’s too intimate. But it is because of this extreme intimacy that the work is powerful. Furthermore, Choukri doesn’t try to embellish the hard and miserable life. He doesn’t romanticize the life on the road. Many times, whether it be in film, literature or music, we get this romantic image of a tramp wandering around, searching for whatever exploits he/she might encounter. That’s not the case here. From the very first page I found myself gripped as Choukri describes the feeling of extreme hunger and crying for that piece of bread, any bread, just anything to eat. We take bread for granted. I can go whenever I want now to the bakery, buy some bread, eat a bite or two, and maybe forget about it until it goes off. For others, bread is life, and hunger is blasphemous. The life of extreme poverty isn’t pretty, and his exploits to some might not be considered moral. But morality has nothing to do with it. No one chooses where he/she is born. You just play with the cars that you are dealt with. While Choukri isn’t proud of his life, he’s not ashamed from it. It is what it is, and it is what shaped him as a man. <br />This extreme rawness was unfrequented and unprecedented in Arabic literature. No one dared to write with such audacity, not only about themselves, but also about marginalized by society. This is a very powerful work that I recommend. It’s not easy to go through as it can be pretty graphic, but truth is not embellished with fancy words here. In the end, this reminds me of a song I love by Ziyad Rahbani: <br /><br />I am not a blasphemer, but hunger is blasphemous. <br />I am not a blasphemer, but illness is blasphemous. <br />I am not a blasphemer, but poverty is blasphemous,<br />And humiliation is blasphemous. <br />I am not a blasphemer, but what do you want me to do when all the blasphemous things combine in me? <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15265664014710235033" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

