<div id="review_3790552631" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3790552631" />
    <a title="Hussnain Babur" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/83979768-hussnain-babur"><img alt="Hussnain Babur" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1573498089p2/83979768.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3790552631?book_show_action=true">Feb 03, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hussnain Babur" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hussnain Babur" href="/user/show/83979768-hussnain-babur">Hussnain Babur</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781846590108" href="/book/show/155766.For_Bread_Alone">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3790552631" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4978616493196656459"><b> mini spoilers </b> <br/>Such a remarkable autobiography, one of its kind. It perfectly shows the habits, traditions, values as well as agony, desperation, helplessness that Morroccan people were extremely vulnerable to in that period, it is more than an autobiography… It is an historical testimony. First half of the book, or better, author’s childhood is full of incapability, torment, misery and violence. And he is not the only one facing that whole Morocco was living in an atmosphere of injustice and p</span>
  <span id="freeText4978616493196656459" style="display:none"><b> mini spoilers </b> <br />Such a remarkable autobiography, one of its kind. It perfectly shows the habits, traditions, values as well as agony, desperation, helplessness that Morroccan people were extremely vulnerable to in that period, it is more than an autobiography… It is an historical testimony. First half of the book, or better, author’s childhood is full of incapability, torment, misery and violence. And he is not the only one facing that whole Morocco was living in an atmosphere of injustice and poverty that they were on the edge of breaking. <br /> <i>“Why doesn’t Allah give us our good luck the way he gives it to other people? I passed the question to my mother. That’s something we can’t ask, she said.” </i> Every single line related to his childhood ended up personifying powerlessness and all that violence he was facing or witnessing ended up making him a part of it, making him think this is how it is supposed to work. Sex, for instance, was ,other than being a method to liberate his frustrations, also a burning violence… he saw his mother beat up but still loving his father made him preassume women want to be get hit and being a “man” even making love is being physically dominating. Society was going towards a moral destruction, I couldn’t sense any islamic value in that society, only some names and religious references to “use” them for their needs. A poverty that leads him to constantly change cities, eventually cut his connection from his violent father… but a sense of strangeness and lack of own-ness hunted him wherever he went, whatever conditions he lived in, from sleeping in a graveyard to prostituting himself. <i>“I prefer jail in my native land to freedom in exile.”</i> We could see the historical events and desperation in people’s lives’ from his eyes, his journey was accompanied with a series of events happening around there, from rebellings to raids, it showed how the time of colonizers was going to end. The desperation and powerlessness also made him say things that would be considered blasphemous but that the same point thought provoking on the fact why is reached at this moment of actually saying this. <i>“He drags back those who are not here, and pronounces judgement on them. Whatever he pleases. Like Allah.” </i><br />One element that struck me a lot was the weakness, the society of that time had no space for weaknesses which are innocence, true love, relationships, sincerity. This is one quote that I loved, it refers to when choukrey’s brother was killed by his own father and his small body was buried in the cemetery and he said <i>“His grave will be invisible among all the others. It will get lost, the way litde things always disappear among the big ones.”</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="4978616493196656459" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


