<div id="review_3417139406" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3417139406" />
    <a title="Altaf Hussain" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/65626220-altaf-hussain"><img alt="Altaf Hussain" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1488706221p2/65626220.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3417139406?book_show_action=true">Mar 18, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Altaf Hussain" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Altaf Hussain" href="/user/show/65626220-altaf-hussain">Altaf Hussain</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781846590108" href="/book/show/155766.For_Bread_Alone">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3417139406" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5363804838194095068">&quot;For bread alone&quot; by Mohamed Choukri was never in my #TBR. Even I didn&apos;t know about it until this Ramzan and I guess this #book is my first book that is written by a #Moroccan #author<br/>.<br/>It&apos;s banned in Morocco and was banned for some time in Arabic countries too. I started reading this book during the banned books week and that was pure coincidence. Plus this book has travelled with me and my Bookay friends on our trip to #Kundmalir #Balochistan. The picture is taken at Princess of Hope, courtesy o</span>
  <span id="freeText5363804838194095068" style="display:none">"For bread alone" by Mohamed Choukri was never in my #TBR. Even I didn't know about it until this Ramzan and I guess this #book is my first book that is written by a #Moroccan #author<br />.<br />It's banned in Morocco and was banned for some time in Arabic countries too. I started reading this book during the banned books week and that was pure coincidence. Plus this book has travelled with me and my Bookay friends on our trip to #Kundmalir #Balochistan. The picture is taken at Princess of Hope, courtesy of @natashafatehm <br />So, thank you.<br />.<br />Speaking about the book, then this book is fictional autobiography of Mohamed Choukri. The story reflects the lives of poor people, cornered by the elite class during colonisation in Morocco. How the divide affects people of different classese differently is well explained. Famine, poverty, fighting for one piece of bread, malnutrition and search for better life resulted in the death of eight of Mohamed's siblings and another one was killed by Mohamed's father in a fit of rage. <br />.<br />How Mohamed survives is worth reading and how he led his life after hitting puberty is another great and very honest reflection of a teenager who did every unbelievable thing during this time. If reading Manto seems cringy to you then pl, never ever pick up this book. This is way ahead and honestly requires patience to surpass few pages here and there.<br />.<br />The two things that I loved about this book are, first, that author is dead honest. After Khushwant Singh and Reza Aslan, Mohamed Choukri has won my heart in writing honestly. Second thing was the whole story of having impact of reading and writing over Choukri. In the jail, when Choukri comes to know about the importance of reading and writing, I sensed his life is going to change there. Even that moment was kind of enlightenment for me too. Those pages are my favourite pages. Overall this book was 3.5/5 for me. <br />.<br />If you need more motivation to read this book then if you like books by Khaled Hosseni then you'll like this book too. I was receiving unintentional connection between these too. Nonetheless, the writing expression of this book is comparatively better.<br />Happy Reading.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5363804838194095068" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

