<div id="review_3413738080" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3413738080" />
    <a title="Angel 一匹狼" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25600796-angel"><img alt="Angel 一匹狼" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1438533669p2/25600796.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3413738080?book_show_action=true">Jul 07, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Angel 一匹狼" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Angel 一匹狼" href="/user/show/25600796-angel">Angel 一匹狼</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 8476600720" href="/book/show/44026441-el-pa-de-cada-dia">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3413738080" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2207122887350021448">&quot;الخبز الحافي&quot; is a surprisingly good book when it goes dark, when it talks about Xukri&apos;s experiences (it is supposed to be autobiographical; as always, the truth in the story can be debatable) in Morocco, the thefts, the police violence, his need for love, his need for food, his family problems, all things that happen since he is a little child till around his twenties. He comes from a poor family, he is illiterate, his father is a violent and selfish man... It creates a atmosphere of horror an</span>
  <span id="freeText2207122887350021448" style="display:none">"الخبز الحافي" is a surprisingly good book when it goes dark, when it talks about Xukri's experiences (it is supposed to be autobiographical; as always, the truth in the story can be debatable) in Morocco, the thefts, the police violence, his need for love, his need for food, his family problems, all things that happen since he is a little child till around his twenties. He comes from a poor family, he is illiterate, his father is a violent and selfish man... It creates a atmosphere of horror and dread that is clearly translated to the reader, and shows, in an engaging manner, the relation between environment, religion, family... and the growing up of a person.<br /><br />It is not so interesting when Xukri forces us to read about all of his sexual encounters, even if it is a way to reflect his needs, his obsessions and his fears. The problem is that it ends up being too repetitive, too much of the same, and it feels kind of the 'I am a rebel and women love me' story-telling. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[And in a couple of situations, it can be quite uncomfortable for some readers <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />However, it is interesting enough (and short) to be worth your time.<br /><br />The best: the mood and atmosphere, the darkness in the story (even if then we have to start with how this reinforces some views on or represents some societies, cultures, etc.)<br /><br />The worst: all the sexual 'adventures'<br /><br />Alternatives: for this kind of fictionalized autobiographies, Karl Ove Knausgård or Thomas Bernhard; even if quite different, "82년생 김지영" is a good option; and if you like your books less novelization of life events and more chemistry try "Uncle Tungsten"<br /><br />6.5/10<br /><br />(Catalan, well, Valencian, translation by Isaïes Minetto Gozálvez)</span>
  <a data-text-id="2207122887350021448" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


